postcontent:
I have to decided to sell my lightly used CZ75B to fund another purchase. I have fired about 500 rounds, so it has basically been broken in and smoothed out for the next owner. The gun comes with the original box, manual, and two magazines. I have six magazines for the gun (One 15-round, four 16-round, and one 17-round), that I will sell with the gun for an additional $20 per magazine. I also have two holsters. One black leather belt holster made by Wild Bill's Concealment out of Garner, NC, and a IWB holster by Theis out of Arkansas. I will part with the holsters for an additional $10 a piece. They are both very high quality.

The CZ 75B is a very accurate pistol. The internal rails lead to the gun being very tight, but very smooth when the slide is moved. The steel frame but not overly hefty, but definitely makes the pistol very easy to shoot with a light recoil. The DA/SA trigger is already smooth, but tends to smooth out even more as the pistol is fired. The low bore axis lends itself to directing the already soft recoil straight back and decreasing the target transition time.

I am asking $500 for the base package, with the the prices for the additional items listed above. If you want to make your own offer, go ahead. The worst I can do is say no.

I require a copy of a valid NC ID and a pistol purchase permit/copy of CHP, upon face to face sale. I will ship if you cover the cost.

title: For Sale/Trade:  2000 Jeep Wrangler TJ 4x4 - clean, might also have other stuff to throw in (trailer, winch, etc.)
postcontent:
Ok, so... I love my jeep, and I always wanted one... but some recent events have me needing a truck. I thought I would put this "feeler" out there to see what might be around. I'm looking for a truck so I can haul stuff and it NEEDS to be an extended or crew cab since I have kids. Also would prefer 4wd since I go camping. For the right deal, I'll throw in my small trailer (new tires) that I was hoping to eventually turn into my expedition trailer (but still works now just to haul smaller stuff around). Also, if it's the right trade, I might throw in a 8000lb Champion winch and winch plate (brand new, still has tags on it) that i've not got around to mounting yet. 

Here are the details

2000 Wrangler TJ sport

The good:
Straight I6 4.0 Engine (just rebuilt earlier this year)

31 inch tires with good tread

Mostly stock, not all beat up or off-roaded (although she could). 

Good exterior and clean interior.

AC/heat

Manual

Desert sand pearl paint scheme is somewhat had to find, and one of my favorites

Radio with AUX input and USB, and sound bar up top.

Needs work:
AC works great, but blower turns off on highest setting. Prob resister block which i'll replace later this week (most likely), still blows cold enough on setting "3"

Soft top needs a few stitches redone, but holds true. Keeps water and wind out as is now.

One fender flare was cracked and repaired with putty. Holds fine, looks ok, but a perfectionist would want replaced.

Shop that rebuilt engine welded the exhaust rather than use the donut that holds it together (since donut was damaged). I think the weld leaks a little because sometime I hear it rattling. 

Hood has a few wavy spots that are hard to see unless you are driving.

Other little odds and ends that I can't think of, but are typical for a 14 year old vehicle.

Overall, I drive this everyday and it runs strong. These I6's are practically bulletproof, and with the rebuilt engine...this one has many many years of life left. 

Title is free and clear.

Ok, so.... if you have a truck you want to trade, email me the info. Truck needs to have 4wd. I will try and respond to everyone who sends up ideas for trade. Obviously I recognize we will have to see each others vehicles for the deal to be finalized. Please understand, that if I'm not interested, I'll try and respond back if I'm not flooded with too many requests (I'm sure I'll get a whole slew of people with old half running trucks looking for a trade, lol). I will just respond with "no thanks", please don't take it personally, it's gonna have to be just the right trade to make me give up my jeep. These TJ jeeps, with the 6 cylinder and rebuilt engine and with these options in this condition is prob worth around $9500 from what i've seen them going for on CL. 

For me to get a truck I want...I'm looking for 9k.

It's in great shape and still looks good for it's age.... of course, pics don't always show the little bumps and bruises. Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  Powder Coated Hard Cast Bullets
postcontent:
Looking for something unique to add to your reloading bench?  Want to have something new to show your shooting buddies?  I have been casting bullets for a few years now, and I always tumble lubed them and coated them in mica powder to make them less sticky.  That works well, but recently I started doing something different.  I heard about people who were powder coating their bullets, so I decided to give it a try and the results are impressive.  The powder coat seals off the outer diameter of the bullet, preventing any contact with the barrel and essentially eliminating lead fouling.  There is no sticky residue and the coating is very slick, acting more like a plated bullet.  I now have several calibers that I stocked up on, and I have a few spares I can now sell.

Prices:
.38 148gr wadcutter (sized .358) - $30 per 500 Coated, $25 Tumble lubed
.40 180gr Truncated Cone (sized .401) - $35 per 500 Coated, $30 TL
.45 230gr Round Nose (sized .452)- $40 per 500 Coated, $35 TL
9mm 124gr Round Nose (sized .356)- $30 per 500 Coated, $25 TL

I have had very good luck coating with red and black, and I highly recommend those two colors.  I am playing around with white and yellow, and have not gotten the consistency with those two yet that I see with red/black.  More experimenting is needed, and I will eventually branch out into more crazy colors as hobby money allows...

Regardless of color, I have seen absolutely no residue in the barrels of any of my guns.  Not from lead or the powder coat, these shoot very clean!

See attached photo for examples - please note: I am not selling loaded ammunition, the loaded rounds shown are simply examples of what the finished product looks like, for your reference.

title: For Trade:  DESERT EAGLE MK I .357 MAG
postcontent:
Hey folks!

I picked up this awesome weapon in trade, but because I already have a hand cannon, I am not as in love with it as I thought. It is an awesome piece, and is a first gen Israeli import pistol. The .357 DE can handle the hottest of loads, and runs flawlessly, chewing through everything. The frame size is slightly smaller than the .44 (slightly) which makes it easier and more comfortable to shoot. The bore has polygonal rifling, much like an HK. 


This is a very early serial number, 83xx... First run!


This pistol is a real show stopper, and is in absolutely stunning condition. The BCG is clean, and there is very, very little handling wear. (Most DE pistols are handled more than they are shot.) 

The pistol will include one magazine and a hard case. 

This variant of DE is far more affordable to shoot, as .357 mag ammo is far cheaper than 44 or 50!

All USPs use a fiber-reinforced polymer frame stiffened by stainless steel inserts at areas subject to stress and friction. HK pioneered this use of polymer materials in the production of handguns more than 30 years ago with the development of the VP70Z and P9S pistols.
The USP control lever, a combination safety and decocking lever, is frame mounted and quickly accessible, unlike the slide-mounted safeties common on many semi-automatic pistols.
Using a modified Browning-type action with a special patented recoil reduction system, the USP recoil reduction system reduces recoil effects on pistol components and also lowers the recoil forces felt by the shooter. This same recoil reduction system has been tested and proven in the HK Mark 23 pistol developed for the U.S. Special Operations Command. The USP recoil reduction system is insensitive to ammunition types and requires no special adjustment or maintenance. It functions effectively in all USP models.
The modular design of the USP's internal components allows the control lever function to be switched from the left to the right side of the pistol for left-handed shooters. The USP can also be converted from one type of trigger firing mode to another. This includes combination double-action and single-action (DA/SA) modes and double action only (DAO) modes.
The USP is available in nine trigger/firing mode configurations and three calibers. 9mm, .40 S&W and .45 ACP.
